# MedinovAI Platform Context

## Identity

MedinovAI is a multi-tenant healthcare, clinical research, and AI platform. Repositories in the
`medinovai-health` GitHub org must align to one platform model instead of inventing local rules.

## Non-Negotiables

- No PHI in logs, prompts, embeddings, fixtures, or comments.
- No cross-tenant access. Every request path must stay tenant-scoped.
- Every state-changing workflow requires an audit trail.
- Least privilege for service accounts, CI tokens, and runtime roles.
- Every deployable service must expose `GET /health`.
- Do not create a new repo when an existing MedinovAI repo should be extended.

## Tier Model

- Tier 0: core libraries and shared contracts
- Tier 1: platform and security services
- Tier 2: domain platform services and orchestration
- Tier 3: clinical, research, and business applications
- Tier 4: frontend and client applications

## Operating Rules

- Prefer standards from `medinovai-Deploy` over repo-local conventions when they conflict.
- Use generated `medinovai.manifest.yaml` values as the source of truth for tier, category, and squad.
- Keep repo automation thin: reusable workflows, shared templates, and policy checks come from the hub.
- Deployable repos must keep `.env.example`, `Dockerfile`, and health checks aligned with the manifest.
- Mobile, library, and documentation repos still receive charters and manifests, but they do not get Docker deployment wiring.

## Squad Mapping

- `infrastructure-squad`: infra, deploy, observability, release automation
- `security-squad`: auth, encryption, privacy, zero-trust controls
- `data-squad`: data services, lineage, analytics, research data fabric
- `clinical-squad`: LIS, CTMS, eTMF, clinical workflows, regulatory tools
- `ai-ml-squad`: model services, LLMs, AI reasoning, agent systems
- `frontend-squad`: web UI, client apps, mobile surfaces, design systems
- `platform-squad`: shared runtime services, developer experience, org tooling
